            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/112af7d90f46baad/text/000000916",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-112af7d90f46baad-58df80 twpub-112af7d90f46baad-25d4bc twpub-112af7d90f46baad-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/112af7d90f46baad/text/000000917": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/112af7d90f46baad/text/000000917",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-112af7d90f46baad-58df80 twpub-112af7d90f46baad-25d4bc twpub-112af7d90f46baad-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnote\"><p><a></a><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/112af7d90f46baad/text/000000530\"><span class=\"label\">[24]</span></$link> P. 108. In France actors were at one time looked upon as excommunicated persons, not worthy of burial in holy ground or with Christian rites. In 1730 the &quot;honours of sepulture&quot; were refused to Mademoiselle Lecouvreur (doubtless the Miss Monime of this passage). Voltaire's miscellaneous works contain a paper on the matter.</p></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/112af7d90f46baad/text/000000918": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/112af7d90f46baad/text/000000918",
